{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17491510","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17491510"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:50:10+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:50:10+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"964"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"964","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/964"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.03,0.45,0.03,0.48]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"964"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97444"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"964","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/964"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"964"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80054"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"251"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"1536"},{"type":"tags","id":"2589"},{"type":"tags","id":"3549"},{"type":"tags","id":"3817"},{"type":"tags","id":"4046"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"736"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22775"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33389"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97444","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/97444"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old man is being managed for a recent, endoscopically diagnosed carcinoma of the stomach. He presented with a one month history of anorexia and weight loss. The physical examination is unremarkable. Before any decision is made on further treatment, such as the potential operability of his disease, evidence of distant metastatic disease needs to be sought and excluded. \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most useful initial investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Liver function tests","Laparoscopy","Positron emission tomographic (PET) scan","Endoscopic ultrasound (EUS) examination","CT chest and abdomen"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EAll the options listed have a potential role to play in the staging of gastric cancer. Once the diagnosis of carcinoma of the stomach has been established, the next investigation should be a \u003Cstrong\u003ECT scan\u003C/strong\u003E. This will help define the size and extent of the primary tumour, the presence of any possible lymph node disease and any distant spread. A CT examination of the chest must be included to look for evidence of mediastinal or supraclavicular lymph node involvement.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELiver function tests are non-specific, but can give a clue that metastatic disease might be present. Endoscopic ultrasound can be used for assessing the T stage of early disease. Provided that the CT scan has not shown any evidence of distant metastatic disease and some form of gastric resection is being considered, laparoscopy is mandatory for excluding peritoneal disease, which might have been missed on CT scanning.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPET scanning has limited use in gastric cancer, as only about 70% are PET-avid.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The CT scan has a key role in the staging of gastric cancers in looking for evidence of metastatic disease."],"references":["Smyth EC, Nilsson M, Grabsch HI, et al. Gastric cancer. Lancet 2020; 396;635-48. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/32861308/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80054"}},